SIMPLE: lyre
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lyre
<hw>Lyre</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>lire</ets>, OF.
<ets>lyre</ets>, L. <ets>lyra</ets>, Gr. <?/. Cf. <er>Lyra</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A stringed instrument of music; a
kind of harp much used by the ancients, as an accompaniment to
poetry.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The lyre was the peculiar instrument of Apollo, the
tutelary god of music and poetry. It gave name to the species of verse
called lyric, to which it originally furnished an
accompaniment.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>One of the constellations;
Lyra. See <er>Lyra</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Lyre bat</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a small bat
(<spn>Megaderma lyra</spn>), inhabiting India and Ceylon. It is
remarkable for the enormous size and curious shape of the nose membrane
and ears.</cd> -- <col><b>Lyre turtle</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>,
<cd>the leatherback.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lyre bird</ent>⟦br⟧
